ve Heaven and Earth explores external factors, like geography, local power dynamics, and genocide timelines, as well as the internal states of mind and motivations of those who effected rescues. Framed within the interdisciplinary scholarship of genocide studies and rooted in cultural anthropology methodologies, Burnet presents stories of heroism and of the good done amidst the evil of a genocide that nearly annihilated Rwandan Tutsi and decimated Hutu and Twa who were opposed to the slaughter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aGenocidezRwandaxHistoryy20th century. 0aRwandan Genocide, Rwanda, 1994. 0aTutsi (African people)xCrimes againstzRwandaxHistoryy20th century. 4aAnthropology. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  amuslims genocide rwanda, altruism in genocide, rwanda genocide religion genocide, rwanda studies, 1994 genocide of tutsi in rwanda.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176713540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501767135423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501767135/original  a978-3-11-075183-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK